494
00:33:22,780 --> 00:33:24,120
to my life?

495
00:33:24,120 --> 00:33:27,180
Like... What? I don't know.

496
00:33:27,180 --> 00:33:28,410
Just off the top of my head,

497
00:33:28,410 --> 00:33:31,870
something like I DNA-tested my dad and found that

498
00:33:31,870 --> 00:33:34,630
he was not my biological father- you are.

499
00:33:36,220 --> 00:33:37,720
That's impossible.

500
00:33:37,720 --> 00:33:40,670
People lie. Birthmarks don't.

501
00:33:46,830 --> 00:33:49,200
Oh, my God!

502
00:33:50,850 --> 00:33:53,060
You told me he was a premie.

503
00:33:53,060 --> 00:33:55,600
<i>This bloody lunatic is my son!</i>

504
00:33:55,600 --> 00:33:57,040
He's not a lunatic.

505
00:33:57,040 --> 00:33:59,620
All those years you could have told me. I could have done things.

506
00:33:59,620 --> 00:34:02,030
That could have made a difference in the boy's life.

507
00:34:02,030 --> 00:34:04,890
I think we should all just calm down. Look at him sitting there-

508
00:34:04,890 --> 00:34:06,990
a pill-popping sociopath!

509
00:34:06,990 --> 00:34:10,400
If you wanted to screw up his life, you couldn't have done it better.

510
00:34:10,400 --> 00:34:11,410
He's got you there, mom.

511
00:34:11,410 --> 00:34:14,810
He's one of the most well-respected doctors in the world.

512
00:34:14,810 --> 00:34:17,700
He's saved more lives than you can count.

513
00:34:18,750 --> 00:34:22,290
Now, you apologize to him, or I swear,

514
00:34:22,290 --> 00:34:24,370
you will never see me again, Thomas.

515
00:34:24,370 --> 00:34:26,680
I can't deal with this anymore.

516
00:34:26,680 --> 00:34:28,260
<i>He's my son?</i>

517
00:34:28,260 --> 00:34:30,600
I'm having a bloody breath of fresh air,

518
00:34:30,600 --> 00:34:32,020
that's what I'm doing.

519
00:34:39,070 --> 00:34:41,120
So, who's for dessert?

520
00:34:46,900 --> 00:34:49,250
Somebody help me!

521
00:34:50,300 --> 00:34:50,900
Uhh! Somebody-

522
00:34:50,900 --> 00:34:53,450
Will? It's Dr. Adams and Dr. Chase.

523
00:34:53,450 --> 00:34:55,860
We just need to know- My eyes! My eyes!

524
00:34:56,120 --> 00:34:57,990
It feels like it's on fire!

525
00:35:07,370 --> 00:35:08,430
It's not behcet's.

526
00:35:08,430 --> 00:35:10,420
It doesn't necrotize tissue like this.

527
00:35:10,420 --> 00:35:12,510
I think it's streptococcus pyogenes.

528
00:35:12,510 --> 00:35:15,760
Except we've already treated him with broad spectrum antibiotics.

529
00:35:15,760 --> 00:35:20,240
It shouldn't be spreading. It should be dying. Just means it's drug-resistant.

530
00:35:20,240 --> 00:35:23,210
We need to remove what's left of his eyes before the gangrene sets in.

531
00:35:23,210 --> 00:35:26,880
It's something that looks and acts like a bacteria but isn't one.

532
00:35:26,880 --> 00:35:28,590
Could be viral. No, it couldn't.

533
00:35:28,590 --> 00:35:31,590
There's no evidence of viral markers in the necrotized tissue.

534
00:35:34,060 --> 00:35:37,720
Let me see that image you took last night of the clot in his lung.

535
00:35:47,040 --> 00:35:49,910
That's not a piece of the clot from his brain.

536
00:35:50,730 --> 00:35:52,710
That's the point of infection.

537
00:35:53,980 --> 00:35:56,030
Mucormycosis.

538
00:35:56,030 --> 00:35:59,790
